Sharpening your AppDynamics approach
Your instinct to use AppD for the top 10 slow queries is right, but "address on regular basis" is too vague to execute. Here's what makes it concrete:
Don't just rank by slowest — rank by frequency × latency. A query that takes 8 seconds but runs once a day is less important than one that takes 1.2 seconds but runs 500 times a minute. AppD gives you both numbers; multiply them to get a pain score.
Categorize before fixing — when you pull the top 10, first categorize each one. Almost every slow query in an enterprise Java app falls into one of four buckets: N+1 (Hibernate lazy loading), missing index, no pagination on large result sets, or cross-module joins that shouldn't exist. The fix is completely different for each. Knowing the category tells you whether the fix is a one-line @BatchSize annotation or a structural query rewrite.
Fix top 3 first, measure, then continue — don't fix all 10 at once. Fix 3, deploy, measure the AppD baseline shift, then move to the next batch. This gives you a feedback loop and a story to tell management ("we improved average response time by 340ms in sprint 3").
Sharpening the prod issues approach
"Address as it comes" is the right reactive instinct but it needs one addition: every prod fix must ship with a regression test and a root cause label. After 6 sprints, you'll have a tagged list of root causes. That list will almost certainly show 2-3 categories responsible for 70% of prod issues — those become your proactive work items.
The other thing to add: a 15-minute weekly review of prod issues from the previous week. Not a big meeting — just the tech lead looking at what came in, tagging the root cause, and deciding whether it's reactive (fix in place) or systemic (add to backlog). This stops the "address as it comes" pattern from being purely firefighting.
The modularization sequencing specifically
Given your system, here's the order I'd extract modules and why:
First: broker-integration — it's already a separate class, it has the most prod and perf issues, and extracting it gives you the circuit breaker and resilience layer that directly addresses management's concerns. Highest visible impact.
Second: questionnaire — it's reused across phases, has no circular dependencies, and once extracted it unblocks clean testing of every other module. It's the enabler.
Third: validation — now that you have characterization tests and two clean modules as reference, the validation extraction is lower risk. The validator logic is complex but contained.
Fourth: cross-cutting modules (audit-trail, notification, task-inbox) — these are straightforward extractions with no domain complexity.
Last: workflow-engine — this is the hardest and highest risk. Save it for when you have full test coverage and confidence from the earlier extractions.
The management narrative
These three tracks give you a clear story at each sprint review:

Sprint 2: "We've reduced average response time by X ms on the top 3 queries and written 40 characterization tests covering our highest-risk workflows."
Sprint 4: "Broker integration is now isolated in its own module with a circuit breaker. The last 3 prod issues in that area have been addressed at root cause, not just patched."
Sprint 8: "Prod issues are down 40% from the peak. We have 4 clean modules with enforced boundaries and a test suite that gives us confidence to move fast."

That's a narrative management can follow and fund. It's not "we're doing modularization" — it's "here's what got better and why."
